<h2>Solar Panels in Maryland</h2>
<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Maryland's solar irradiance levels average 4.4 peak sun hours daily, with significant seasonal variation that homeowners should understand when planning their systems. During peak summer months (June through August), daily solar irradiance can reach 5.5-6.0 peak sun hours, while winter months (December through February) typically see 2.5-3.0 peak sun hours. This seasonal variation means a typical residential solar system will produce approximately 60% more electricity in summer compared to winter months.</p>

<p>A standard 6kW residential solar system in Maryland can be expected to generate approximately 7,200-7,800 kWh annually, which covers 70-90% of typical household electricity consumption. The state's relatively moderate climate means solar panels operate efficiently year-round, with cooler temperatures in fall, winter, and spring actually improving panel efficiency compared to extremely hot climates. Maryland's location at approximately 39¬∞N latitude makes it ideal for fixed-tilt solar installations, with optimal panel angles between 30-40 degrees facing south.</p>

<p>Regional variations within Maryland can affect solar production, with the eastern shore and southern counties receiving slightly more solar irradiance than northern and western mountainous regions. However, even in lower-irradiance areas, solar remains highly economically viable due to the state's favorable net metering policies and incentive programs.</p>

