<h2>HVAC Systems in Maryland</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Maryland's humid subtropical climate requires HVAC systems capable of handling both significant cooling and heating loads throughout the year. Summer temperatures regularly exceed 85¬∞F with high humidity levels that can make it feel even hotter, while winter temperatures frequently drop below freezing. This climate profile means homeowners need approximately 60% cooling and 40% heating on an annual basis, though this varies significantly between northern and southern regions of the state.</p>

<p>For Maryland homes, HVAC professionals typically recommend air conditioning systems with SEER (Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio) ratings of at least 16, though systems with SEER 18-20 provide optimal efficiency and comfort. Heat pumps are particularly well-suited to Maryland's moderate climate, as they can provide both heating and cooling efficiently. Modern cold-climate heat pumps can operate effectively down to -5¬∞F, making them viable primary heating sources for most Maryland locations.</p>

<p>Humidity control is crucial in Maryland, especially during summer months when relative humidity can exceed 70%. HVAC systems should include proper dehumidification capabilities, and homes may benefit from whole-house dehumidifiers to maintain indoor humidity levels between 30-50% for optimal comfort and indoor air quality. Additionally, proper sizing is critical ‚Äì oversized systems will short-cycle and fail to adequately remove humidity, while undersized systems will struggle to maintain comfort during peak load conditions.</p>

