<h2>Maryland Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Maryland offers some of the most comprehensive incentive programs for solar and energy efficiency improvements on the East Coast, making renewable energy and efficient HVAC systems highly attractive investments for homeowners.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> The 30% federal tax credit applies to the total cost of solar panel systems, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work. For a typical \$18,000 solar installation, this credit provides \$5,400 in tax savings. The credit applies to both residential and commercial installations and can be carried forward if it exceeds your tax liability in the installation year. This credit is scheduled to remain at 30% through 2032, then step down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034.</li>

<li><strong>Maryland Solar Grant Program:</strong> The state provides grants up to \$1,000 for residential solar installations, administered through the Maryland Energy Administration. These grants are available on a first-come, first-served basis and can be combined with federal tax credits for maximum savings. Income-qualified households may be eligible for additional grant amounts up to \$6,000.</li>

<li><strong>BGE Energy Efficiency Programs:</strong> Baltimore Gas and Electric offers rebates for high-efficiency HVAC systems, including up to \$300 for heat pumps with SEER 16+ ratings, \$500 for geothermal systems, and additional rebates for smart thermostats (\$75-\$100). BGE also provides free energy audits and weatherization services that can identify opportunities for additional energy savings.</li>

<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Solar energy systems are exempt from property tax assessment increases in Maryland, meaning the added home value from solar installation won't increase your property taxes. This exemption can save hundreds of dollars annually over the system's lifetime.</li>

<li><strong>Net Metering:</strong> Maryland's net metering program allows solar system owners to receive credit for excess electricity sent to the grid at the full retail rate. This effectively allows you to use the grid as a battery, banking excess summer production to offset winter consumption.</li>

<li><strong>Solar Renewable Energy Certificates (SRECs):</strong> Maryland maintains an active SREC market where solar system owners can sell certificates representing the environmental benefits of their solar production. Current SREC prices range from \$50-\$80 per MWh, providing an additional revenue stream that can add \$300-\$600 annually to system savings.</li>
</ul>

